---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Navbar from '../components/Navbar.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../components/seo/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import JsonLd from '../components/seo/JsonLd.astro';
import LastUpdated from '../components/seo/LastUpdated.astro';
import ScheduleQuiz from '../components/ScheduleQuiz.astro';
import { getCanonicalUrl } from '../lib/seo/metadata';
import { buildBreadcrumbSchema, buildFAQSchema, buildWebPageSchema } from '../lib/seo/schema';

const title = 'Best Custody Schedule for a 5-Year-Old | Examples, Calendar & Tips';
const description =
	'Compare the best custody schedules for a 5-year-old with calendar examples, school tips, overnight estimates, and planning tools.';
const canonical = '/best-custody-schedule-for-5-year-old/';
const canonicalUrl = getCanonicalUrl(canonical);

const breadcrumbs = [
	{ name: 'Home', url: getCanonicalUrl('/') },
	{ name: 'Guides', url: getCanonicalUrl('/blog/') },
	{ name: 'Best Custody Schedule for a 5-Year-Old', url: canonicalUrl },
];

const faqItems = [
	{
		question: 'What is the best custody schedule for a 5-year-old?',
		answer:
			'For many families, a 2-2-5-5 or 5-2-2-5 custody schedule is a strong starting point for a 5-year-old because it can balance school-week stability, regular time with both parents, and alternating weekends. The best schedule still depends on distance between homes, school logistics, parent work schedules, how the child handles transitions, and whether both homes can manage bedtime and school mornings. A good plan should work on a normal school day, not just look fair on a calendar.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Is a 50/50 custody schedule good for a 5-year-old?',
		answer:
			'A 50/50 custody schedule can work well for a 5-year-old when both parents live close to school, communicate well, and can maintain bedtime, morning, and school routines. Equal parenting time is usually more practical when both homes are prepared for backpacks, lunch boxes, school notices, clothing, and transportation. If exchanges are high conflict, homes are far apart, or the child becomes unsettled after transitions, a 60/40 or modified schedule may be easier.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Is week-on week-off too long for a 5-year-old?',
		answer:
			'Week-on/week-off may work for some mature 5-year-olds, especially when both homes are calm, close to school, and already familiar. Many families still find a full week away from one parent feels long at this age. Shorter 50/50 patterns such as 2-2-5-5 or 5-2-2-5 often give more frequent contact while keeping the calendar predictable. If week-on/week-off is used, video calls or a midweek dinner may help.',
	},
	{
		question: 'How many exchanges per week are best for a 5-year-old?',
		answer:
			'There is no perfect number, but many 5-year-olds do better when exchanges are predictable and not rushed. Two or three exchanges per week may work if homes are close, transitions are calm, and school supplies are organized. Fewer exchanges may be better when distance, conflict, or school mornings make handoffs stressful. The quality of the exchange matters too: a calm school pickup may be easier than a tense evening handoff.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What if my 5-year-old cries before exchanges?',
		answer:
			'Crying before exchanges does not automatically mean the custody schedule is wrong. Some children cry because transitions are hard, they are tired, or they sense tension between parents. Look for patterns: every exchange, only after long weekends, or only when pickup is rushed. A consistent goodbye routine, school-based exchanges, a visual custody calendar, or fewer last-minute changes may help. If distress is intense or ongoing, consider reviewing the parenting plan with a qualified professional.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Should a 5-year-old have the same schedule as older siblings?',
		answer:
			'Keeping siblings together can be helpful, but it is not the only factor. A teenager may handle week-on/week-off well, while a 5-year-old may need more frequent contact or a more predictable bedtime routine. Some families use the same household schedule for simplicity. Others adjust calls, exchange times, or summer blocks to fit each child’s age. The goal is to avoid designing the younger child’s week only around an older sibling’s independence.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What is the best visitation schedule for a 5-year-old if parents live far apart?',
		answer:
			'If parents live far apart, frequent midweek exchanges may be difficult because travel can interfere with school nights, bedtime, and morning routines. A 60/40 schedule, every other weekend schedule with a midweek visit, or another lower-exchange plan may be more realistic than strict 50/50. Long-distance plans often need clearer holiday, summer, and school-break language because those periods may preserve meaningful time with the parent who lives farther away.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Should holidays be separate from the regular custody schedule?',
		answer:
			'Yes. Most parenting plans handle holidays, school breaks, birthdays, and summer time separately from the regular weekly schedule so important days do not depend only on whose normal day it is. For a 5-year-old, holiday planning should make clear where the child wakes up, who handles transportation, and when the regular schedule resumes. Written rules can prevent confusion around winter break, Thanksgiving, spring break, birthdays, and school closure days.',
	},
	{
		question: 'How do I calculate overnights for a 5-year-old custody schedule?',
		answer:
			'Start with the actual calendar, not just the schedule label. Count where the child sleeps each night, then adjust for holidays, school breaks, summer time, and any custom exchange rules. A 50/50 schedule is often close to 182 or 183 overnights per parent, but the exact number can change based on the start date and holiday rules. Parents can use a custody percentage calculator or parenting time calculator to compare the yearly totals before putting the schedule into a parenting plan.',
	},
];

const comparisonRows = [
	{
		schedule: '2-2-5-5',
		schoolStability: 'High',
		contact: 'High',
		transitionFrequency: 'Medium',
		travelFriendly: 'Medium',
		bestAgeFit: '5–12',
		bestFor: 'Equal time with predictable weekdays',
	},
	{
		schedule: '5-2-2-5',
		schoolStability: 'High',
		contact: 'High',
		transitionFrequency: 'Medium',
		travelFriendly: 'Medium',
		bestAgeFit: '5–14',
		bestFor: 'Families wanting consistent weekday blocks',
	},
	{
		schedule: '2-2-3',
		schoolStability: 'Medium',
		contact: 'Very high',
		transitionFrequency: 'High',
		travelFriendly: 'Low',
		bestAgeFit: '3–8',
		bestFor: 'Younger children needing frequent contact',
	},
	{
		schedule: 'Week-on/week-off',
		schoolStability: 'High',
		contact: 'Medium',
		transitionFrequency: 'Low',
		travelFriendly: 'High',
		bestAgeFit: '8+',
		bestFor: 'Older or very adaptable children',
	},
	{
		schedule: 'Every other weekend',
		schoolStability: 'High',
		contact: 'Lower',
		transitionFrequency: 'Low',
		travelFriendly: 'High',
		bestAgeFit: 'Any age',
		bestFor: 'Distance, high conflict, or limited availability',
	},
];

const tools = [
	{ title: 'Generate a Printable Calendar', href: '/custody-schedule-generator/', description: 'Compare common schedules and create a printable custody calendar.' },
	{ title: 'Calculate Parenting Time Percentage', href: '/custody-percentage-calculator/', description: 'Estimate parenting time percentages from overnights.' },
	{ title: 'Parenting Time Calculator', href: '/parenting-time-calculator/', description: 'Review parenting time totals before choosing a schedule.' },
	{ title: 'Custody Calendar Template', href: '/custody-calendar-template/', description: 'Turn a schedule into a simple calendar parents can review.' },
	{ title: 'Create a Written Parenting Plan', href: '/parenting-plan-template/', description: 'Document exchange times, holidays, school breaks, and expectations.' },
	{ title: '50/50 Custody Schedule', href: '/50-50-custody-schedule/', description: 'Compare equal-time schedules, including 2-2-5-5 and 5-2-2-5.' },
	{ title: 'Plan Holidays Separately', href: '/holiday-custody-schedule/', description: 'Plan holidays and school breaks separately from the weekly schedule.' },
];

const twoTwoFiveFiveRows = [
	['Monday', 'Parent A'],
	['Tuesday', 'Parent A'],
	['Wednesday', 'Parent B'],
	['Thursday', 'Parent B'],
	['Friday', 'Parent A'],
	['Saturday', 'Parent A'],
	['Sunday', 'Parent A'],
	['Next Monday', 'Parent A'],
	['Next Tuesday', 'Parent A'],
	['Next Wednesday', 'Parent B'],
	['Next Thursday', 'Parent B'],
	['Next Friday', 'Parent B'],
	['Next Saturday', 'Parent B'],
	['Next Sunday', 'Parent B'],
];

const decisionRows = [
	['Child is starting kindergarten', '2-2-5-5 or 5-2-2-5', 'Consistent school-night pattern'],
	['Child struggles with transitions', '5-2-2-5 or 60/40', 'Fewer disruptive exchanges'],
	['Parents live within 15 minutes', '2-2-5-5', 'Easier school pickup and frequent contact'],
	['Parents live 30–60 minutes apart', '60/40 or every other weekend plus midweek time', 'Less travel stress'],
	['One parent travels for work', 'Modified 60/40 or 70/30', 'More realistic around availability'],
	['Both parents want equal time', '2-2-5-5 or 5-2-2-5', 'Balanced time without full-week separation'],
	['Parents have high conflict', 'Fewer exchanges, school-based exchanges, or 70/30', 'Reduces direct contact'],
	['Long-distance parenting', 'Every other weekend plus holidays/summer', 'More practical travel schedule'],
];

const overnightRows = [
	['50/50', '182–183', '182–183', 'Equal parenting time'],
	['60/40', 'About 219', 'About 146', 'One parent has more school nights'],
	['70/30', 'About 255', 'About 110', 'Primary home with regular visitation'],
	['80/20', 'About 292', 'About 73', 'Every other weekend style arrangement'],
];

const ageComparisonRows = [
	['Toddler', 'Shorter separations and frequent contact', '/best-custody-schedule-for-toddler/', 'Best custody schedule for a toddler'],
	['5-Year-Old', 'School routine plus frequent parent contact', '/best-custody-schedule-for-5-year-old/', 'Current guide'],
	['7-Year-Old', 'More school and activity structure', '/best-custody-schedule-for-7-year-old/', 'Best custody schedule for a 7-year-old'],
	['Teenager', 'Activities, independence, and longer blocks', '/best-custody-schedule-for-teenager/', 'Best custody schedule for a teenager'],
];

const schema = [
	buildFAQSchema(faqItems),
	buildBreadcrumbSchema(breadcrumbs),
	{
		...buildWebPageSchema({ name: title, description, url: canonicalUrl }),
		dateModified: '2026-06-11',
		isAccessibleForFree: true,
		about: [
			'best custody schedule for 5 year old',
			'custody schedule for 5 year old',
			'parenting plan for 5 year old',
			'custody calendar',
		],
	},
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical}>
	<JsonLd slot="head" data={schema} />
	<Navbar />
	<Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbs} />
	<main>
		<section class="container-shell py-10 lg:py-14">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Custody schedules by age</p>
				<h1 class="mt-4 max-w-4xl text-5xl font-semibold leading-[0.98] tracking-[-0.055em] text-primary lg:text-6xl">
					Best Custody Schedule for a 5-Year-Old
				</h1>
				<LastUpdated />
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 text-base leading-8 text-secondary lg:grid-cols-[1.2fr_0.8fr]">
					<div class="grid gap-4">
						<p>
							Age five is a transition age. Many children are starting kindergarten, moving from preschool routines into school mornings, and learning how to handle longer days away from each parent. The best custody schedule for a 5 year old usually balances emotional security with practical school logistics.
						</p>
						<p>
							A strong custody schedule for 5 year old children should make mornings predictable, keep bedtime realistic, support frequent contact with both parents, and avoid chaotic exchanges. The schedule does not have to be perfect on paper. It has to work on school nights, during sick days, after birthday parties, and when a backpack or lunchbox gets left at the wrong house.
						</p>
						<p>
							The right plan depends on the kindergarten routine, distance between homes, each parent’s work schedule, how well the child handles transitions, how well parents communicate, and whether both parents can manage school mornings and bedtime routines without turning every exchange into a crisis.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5 text-sm leading-6">
						<p class="font-semibold text-primary">Planning note</p>
						<p class="mt-2 text-secondary">
							This guide is for general educational purposes and is not legal advice. Custody decisions should be based on your child’s needs, your parenting plan, and any court orders or local rules that apply.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="mt-8 flex flex-col gap-3 sm:flex-row">
					<a href="/custody-schedule-generator/" class="btn-primary inline-flex h-12 w-full items-center justify-center rounded-full px-7 text-sm font-semibold transition-all duration-200 ease-out hover:-translate-y-px sm:w-auto">
						Use the Custody Schedule Generator
					</a>
					<a href="#comparison-table" class="btn-secondary inline-flex h-12 w-full items-center justify-center rounded-full px-7 text-sm font-semibold transition-all duration-200 ease-out hover:-translate-y-px sm:w-auto">
						Compare schedules
					</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Practical recommendation</p>
				<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Our Practical Recommendation</h2>
				<div class="mt-5 grid gap-5 text-base leading-8 text-secondary lg:grid-cols-[1.15fr_0.85fr]">
					<div class="grid gap-4">
						<p>
							For many 5-year-olds, the best starting point is usually a <a href="/2-2-5-5-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">2-2-5-5 custody schedule</a>, followed closely by a <a href="/5-2-2-5-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">5-2-2-5 custody schedule</a>. Both patterns can keep school nights predictable while giving the child frequent contact with both parents.
						</p>
						<p>
							A <a href="/2-2-3-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">2-2-3 schedule</a> can work if the child handles frequent transitions well, but it may feel busy once kindergarten starts. Week-on/week-off may work better for older children. Every other weekend may be more realistic for long-distance parenting, high-conflict exchanges, or unequal parent availability.
						</p>
						<p>
							This is not legal advice. The best schedule depends on distance between homes, the school routine, parent work schedules, transportation, and how the child adjusts after exchanges. Use the <a href="/custody-schedule-generator/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">Custody Schedule Generator</a> to test a pattern against your real week before deciding it is workable.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
						<p class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary">Best first comparison</p>
						<ol class="mt-3 grid gap-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
							<li>1. 2-2-5-5 custody schedule</li>
							<li>2. 5-2-2-5 custody schedule</li>
							<li>3. 2-2-3 only if transitions are smooth</li>
						</ol>
						<div class="mt-5 grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-1">
							<a href="/custody-schedule-generator/" class="btn-primary inline-flex h-11 items-center justify-center rounded-full px-5 text-sm font-semibold">Open generator</a>
							<a href="/2-2-5-5-custody-schedule/" class="btn-secondary inline-flex h-11 items-center justify-center rounded-full px-5 text-sm font-semibold">Review 2-2-5-5</a>
							<a href="/5-2-2-5-custody-schedule/" class="btn-secondary inline-flex h-11 items-center justify-center rounded-full px-5 text-sm font-semibold">Review 5-2-2-5</a>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<ScheduleQuiz title="Find a Starting Custody Schedule for Your 5-Year-Old" ageGroup="five" />

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[0.8fr_1.2fr]">
				<div>
					<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">What age five needs</p>
					<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">What a 5-Year-Old Needs From a Custody Schedule</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
						At five, children often understand routines better than toddlers, but they still rely on adults to make transitions predictable.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
					{[
						['Predictable mornings', 'School or kindergarten mornings should feel routine. Clothing, lunch, backpacks, medication, and transportation need a clear plan in both homes.'],
						['Stable bedtime', 'A 5 year old custody schedule works better when bedtime expectations are similar enough that the child is not constantly resetting.'],
						['Frequent contact', 'Many children this age still benefit from seeing both parents regularly instead of going long stretches without contact.'],
						['Simple exchanges', 'Exchanges should be easy to understand: after school, after dinner, or at a consistent pickup time. Avoid vague handoffs.'],
						['Time to settle', 'A child needs enough time in each home to unpack, play, sleep, and feel settled, not just arrive and leave again.'],
						['Few surprises', 'Last-minute changes can be hard at this age. When changes are necessary, simple explanations and advance notice help.'],
					].map(([heading, text]) => (
						<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
							<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">{heading}</h3>
							<p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">{text}</p>
						</article>
					))}
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="max-w-3xl">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Sample calendars</p>
				<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Visual Calendar Examples</h2>
				<p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
					These examples show the same common alternating weekday/weekend structure that many parents compare for kindergarten-age children. Some parents call it 2-2-5-5 because they start with the two-day weekday blocks. Others call it 5-2-2-5 because they emphasize the longer five-day blocks.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="mt-6 grid gap-5 lg:grid-cols-2">
				{[
					['2-2-5-5 Example', 'Parent A has Monday and Tuesday, Parent B has Wednesday and Thursday, and weekends alternate.'],
					['5-2-2-5 Example', 'This is often the same practical rhythm, described from the five-day blocks: five days with one parent, two with the other, two back, then five with the other parent.'],
				].map(([heading, description]) => (
					<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
						<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">{heading}</h3>
						<p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">{description}</p>
						<div class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto rounded-[1.25rem] border border-line bg-surface">
							<table class="min-w-[560px] w-full text-left text-sm">
								<thead class="bg-surface-elevated text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-muted">
									<tr>
										<th class="px-3 py-3">Week</th>
										<th class="px-3 py-3">Mon</th>
										<th class="px-3 py-3">Tue</th>
										<th class="px-3 py-3">Wed</th>
										<th class="px-3 py-3">Thu</th>
										<th class="px-3 py-3">Fri</th>
										<th class="px-3 py-3">Sat</th>
										<th class="px-3 py-3">Sun</th>
									</tr>
								</thead>
								<tbody class="divide-y divide-line text-secondary">
									<tr>
										<td class="px-3 py-3 font-semibold text-primary">Week 1</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent A</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent A</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent B</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent B</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent A</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent A</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent A</td>
									</tr>
									<tr>
										<td class="px-3 py-3 font-semibold text-primary">Week 2</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent A</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent A</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent B</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent B</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent B</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent B</td>
										<td class="px-3 py-3">Parent B</td>
									</tr>
								</tbody>
							</table>
						</div>
					</article>
				))}
			</div>
			<div class="mt-5 soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
				<p>
					Want to generate this with your own start date? Use the <a href="/custody-schedule-generator/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">Custody Schedule Generator</a>. To compare parenting-time totals after holidays and school breaks, use the <a href="/custody-percentage-calculator/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">Custody Percentage Calculator</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Find the Best Custody Schedule for Your Situation</h2>
			<p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
				Use the situation, not just the schedule name, to narrow your options. A 50/50 plan can be excellent when homes are close, but a lower-exchange plan may be kinder to the child when travel or conflict is a daily problem.
			</p>
			<div class="mt-6 overflow-x-auto rounded-[1.5rem] border border-line bg-surface shadow-[0_18px_44px_rgba(15,23,42,0.06)]">
				<table class="min-w-[820px] w-full text-left text-sm">
					<thead class="bg-surface-elevated text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-muted">
						<tr>
							<th class="px-4 py-3">Family Situation</th>
							<th class="px-4 py-3">Schedule to Consider</th>
							<th class="px-4 py-3">Why It May Work</th>
						</tr>
					</thead>
					<tbody class="divide-y divide-line text-secondary">
						{decisionRows.map(([situation, schedule, reason]) => (
							<tr>
								<td class="px-4 py-4 font-semibold text-primary">{situation}</td>
								<td class="px-4 py-4">{schedule}</td>
								<td class="px-4 py-4">{reason}</td>
							</tr>
						))}
					</tbody>
				</table>
			</div>
			<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
				If equal time is the goal, start with a <a href="/50-50-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">50/50 custody schedule</a>. If travel or conflict makes equal time unrealistic, compare <a href="/60-40-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">60/40</a>, <a href="/70-30-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">70/30</a>, or every-other-weekend options.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Practical Factors Often Considered When Building a Schedule</h2>
				<p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
					This is not legal advice, but these are common practical factors parents often discuss in parenting plans, mediation, or custody negotiations.
				</p>
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
					<span>• Child’s age and developmental needs</span>
					<span>• School attendance and school district</span>
					<span>• Distance between homes</span>
					<span>• Parent work schedules</span>
					<span>• Transportation responsibilities</span>
					<span>• Communication between parents</span>
					<span>• Existing caregiving routines</span>
					<span>• Sibling schedules</span>
					<span>• Extracurricular activities</span>
					<span>• Medical, emotional, or educational needs</span>
					<span>• Ability to keep exchanges calm</span>
				</div>
				<p class="mt-5 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
					A written <a href="/parenting-plan-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">parenting plan template</a> or <a href="/custody-schedule-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">custody schedule template</a> can help turn these factors into clear exchange rules.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-2">
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Kindergarten and School Considerations</h2>
					<div class="mt-4 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						<p>School changes the custody schedule. Pickup and drop-off, lunch boxes, school forms, reading logs, homework, and teacher communication all need a system. A schedule that works during preschool may need more structure once school mornings matter.</p>
						<p>Many parents find that school-based exchanges reduce conflict because the child is dropped off by one parent and picked up by the other. This can avoid face-to-face handoffs and make the exchange feel like part of the normal school day.</p>
						<p>Parents should also decide what happens on teacher workdays, snow days, school closure days, field trips, and parent-teacher conferences. A <a href="/parenting-plan-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">parenting plan template</a> can help put those details in writing.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Sample Parenting Plan Language for a 5-Year-Old</h2>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">These are examples for planning discussions, not legal advice or required wording.</p>
					<div class="mt-4 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
						<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">School exchange clause:</span> “When school is in session, exchanges will occur through school whenever practical. One parent will drop the child off at school, and the other parent will pick the child up after school.”</p>
						<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Bedtime routine clause:</span> “Both parents will make reasonable efforts to maintain a consistent bedtime routine on school nights.”</p>
						<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">School communication clause:</span> “Both parents may receive school notices, attend school events, and communicate with teachers unless restricted by court order.”</p>
						<p><span class="font-semibold text-primary">Sick child clause:</span> “If the child is sick on an exchange day, the parents will communicate as early as possible and decide whether the exchange should proceed, be delayed, or occur at another agreed time.”</p>
					</div>
					<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
						For a fuller draft, compare a <a href="/parenting-plan-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">parenting plan template</a> with a <a href="/custody-schedule-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">custody schedule template</a>.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

