					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">When 50/50 Custody May Not Be Best for a 5-Year-Old</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						A 50/50 custody schedule for 5 year old children can be positive when both homes are stable and close to school. It may be harder when parents live far apart, exchanges are high conflict, bedtime routines vary widely, work schedules change often, or the child struggles with frequent transitions.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						In those situations, parents often compare a <a href="/60-40-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">60/40 custody schedule</a>, 70/30 schedule, or 80/20 schedule before deciding what is realistic.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Holiday and School Break Planning</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						The regular weekly schedule is only part of a parenting plan. Parents should define Thanksgiving, Christmas or winter break, spring break, summer break, birthdays, Mother's Day, Father's Day, and school closure days.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						Use a <a href="/holiday-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">holiday custody schedule</a>, <a href="/holiday-visitation-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">holiday visitation schedule</a>, and <a href="/parenting-plan-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">parenting plan template</a> to write down details before conflict starts.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

