		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-2">
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Warning Signs the Schedule May Need Adjustment</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						These signs do not automatically mean the schedule is wrong, but they may suggest the family should simplify transitions, adjust exchange times, or review the parenting plan.
					</p>
					<ul class="mt-4 grid gap-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
						<li>• The child becomes very anxious before exchanges.</li>
						<li>• Sleep is disrupted after nearly every transition.</li>
						<li>• School items are often forgotten or duplicated in a stressful way.</li>
						<li>• The child is repeatedly late to school after exchanges.</li>
						<li>• The child seems unsettled after every transition, not just occasionally.</li>
						<li>• Parents argue at nearly every exchange.</li>
						<li>• Schedule changes happen so often that the child cannot predict the week.</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">School Year vs. Summer Schedule</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						A 5-year-old may need a more structured schedule during school months than during summer. Some families use 2-2-5-5 during the school year because it keeps weekday routines stable, then allow longer blocks during summer when school mornings are not the limiting factor.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						Summer can allow more extended time with each parent, but holidays and vacations should still be written separately from the regular weekly schedule. A <a href="/custody-calendar-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">custody calendar template</a> can help parents see how school breaks interact with the normal rotation.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						Build a holiday plan separately with a <a href="/holiday-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">holiday custody schedule</a> or <a href="/holiday-visitation-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">holiday visitation schedule</a> so vacations do not accidentally rewrite the school-year plan.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Making Custody Exchanges Easier for a 5-Year-Old</h2>
				<p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
					For a 5-year-old, the exchange routine can matter as much as the schedule. Small systems reduce stress and make the custody calendar feel predictable.
				</p>
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
					<span>• Use school-based exchanges when possible.</span>
					<span>• Keep duplicate pajamas, toiletries, and comfort items in both homes.</span>
					<span>• Pack backpacks and school items the night before.</span>
					<span>• Use a shared custody calendar.</span>
					<span>• Keep bedtime routines similar.</span>
					<span>• Avoid adult conflict during pickup and drop-off.</span>
					<span>• Give simple reminders instead of long explanations.</span>
					<span>• Use the same exchange time each week when possible.</span>
					<span>• Plan for sick days and school closures.</span>
				</div>
				<p class="mt-5 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
					A <a href="/custody-calendar-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">custody calendar template</a> and written holiday rules can make these routines easier to follow.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Example Family Scenarios</h2>
			<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 lg:grid-cols-3">
				<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
					<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">Nearby homes and kindergarten pickup</h3>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">The parents live 8 minutes apart, both can handle school pickup, and the child is in kindergarten. A 2-2-5-5 schedule is often a practical starting point because it keeps frequent contact with both parents and predictable school days.</p>
				</article>
				<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
					<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">Longer drives after school</h3>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">The parents live 45–60 minutes apart, and the child gets tired after long drives. A <a href="/60-40-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">60/40 schedule</a> or <a href="/every-other-weekend-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">every other weekend schedule</a> with a midweek dinner or visit, if practical, may reduce travel stress and school-night disruption.</p>
				</article>
				<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
					<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">Anxiety and forgotten school items</h3>
					<p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">The child becomes anxious before exchanges and often forgets school items. A 5-2-2-5 schedule or another plan with fewer confusing transitions may help. The issue may not be custody time itself, but the number, timing, and organization of exchanges. A <a href="/custody-calendar-template/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">custody calendar template</a> can make the week easier to see.</p>
				</article>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">What Parents Often Underestimate</h2>
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary md:grid-cols-2">
					<p>School logistics are often harder than the schedule looks on paper. Backpacks, lunch boxes, school forms, medication, uniforms, library books, and extra clothes all have to move with the child or exist in both homes.</p>
					<p>A schedule can be mathematically fair and still feel stressful if exchanges happen at bad times. A 6 p.m. handoff after a long school day may be harder than a school-based exchange, even when the overnight count is identical.</p>
					<p>Many children handle transitions better when each home has duplicate basics: pajamas, toothbrushes, favorite snacks, comfort items, and school supplies. This reduces the feeling that the child is constantly packing for a trip.</p>
					<p>The best schedule is often the one parents can follow consistently for months, not the one that looks perfect in theory. Predictable routines usually help more than constant small adjustments.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-section">
